06369nam a22009015i 9780824860165DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20072007hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248601657 a10.1515/97808248601652doi  a(DE-B1597)483811  a(OCoLC)256728783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ4487b.B82 2007 7aREL0070202bisacsh04a294.3/42304aThe Buddhist Dead :bPractices, Discourses, Representations /ced. by Jacqueline I. Stone, Bryan J. Cuevas. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (528 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKuroda Studies in East Asian Buddhism ;v3500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Buddha’s Funeral -- t2. Cross-Dressing with the Dead -- t3. The Moment of Death in Daoxuan’s Vinaya Commentary -- t4. The Secret Art of Dying -- t5. The Deathbed Image of Master Hongyi -- t6. Dying Like Milarépa -- t7. Fire and the Sword -- t8. Passage to Fudaraku -- t9. The Death and Return of Lady Wangzin -- t10. Gone but Not Departed -- t11. Mulian in the Land of Snows and King Gesar in Hell -- t12. Chinese Buddhist Death Ritual and the Transformation of Japanese Kinship -- t13. Grave Changes -- t14. Care for Buddhism -- tChinese and Korean Character Glossary -- tJapanese Character Glossary -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn its teachings, practices, and institutions, Buddhism in its varied Asian forms has been—and continues to be—centrally concerned with death and the dead. Yet surprisingly "death in Buddhism" has received little sustained scholarly attention. The Buddhist Dead offers the first comparative investigation of this topic across the major Buddhist cultures of India, Sri Lanka, China, Japan, Tibet, and Burma. Its individual essays, representing a range of methods, shed light on a rich array of traditional Buddhist practices for the dead and dying; the sophisticated but often paradoxical discourses about death and the dead in Buddhist texts; and the varied representations of the dead and the afterlife found in Buddhist funerary art and popular literature.This important collection moves beyond the largely text—and doctrine—centered approaches characterizing an earlier generation of Buddhist scholarship and expands its treatment of death to include ritual, devotional, and material culture.Contributors: James A. Benn, Raoul Birnbaum, Jason A. Carbine, Bryan J. Cuevas, Hank Glassman, John Clifford Holt, Matthew T. Kapstein, D. Max Moerman, Mark Rowe, Kurtis R. Schaeffer, Gregory Schopen, Koichi Shinohara, Jacqueline I. Stone, John S. Strong.13 illus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBuddhismxCustoms and practices. 0aDeathxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh1 aBenn, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirnbaum, Raoul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbine, Jason A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuevas, Bryan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuevas, Bryan J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlassman, Hank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt, John Clifford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapstein, Matthew T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoerman, D. Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowe, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaeffer, Kurt